The key ideals mentioned in the Preamble of the Constitution of India are:

- To constitute India into a "SOVEREIGN SOCIALIST SECULAR DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC";
- To secure to all its citizens:
  - "JUSTICE, social, economic and political";
  - "LIBERTY of thought, expression, belief, faith and worship";
  - "EQUALITY of status and of opportunity";
- To promote among all citizens "FRATERNITY assuring the dignity of the individual and the unity and integrity of the Nation."

These ideals were solemnly resolved and adopted by the Constituent Assembly on the twenty-sixth day of November, 1949.

The policy explicitly prohibits fraudulent claims and defines fraud as acts intended to deceive the insurer. If any claim made by the Insured Person is fraudulent in any respect, or supported by false statements, declarations, or fraudulent means or devices used by the Insured Person or anyone acting on their behalf, then all benefits under the policy and the premium paid shall be forfeited. Any amounts already paid on such fraudulent claims must be repaid jointly and severally by all recipients/policyholders who made those claims. Fraud includes:

i. Suggesting as a fact something untrue which the Insured Person does not believe to be true;

ii. Actively concealing facts with knowledge or belief of those facts;

iii. Any other act fitted to deceive;

iv. Any act or omission lawfully declared fraudulent.

The insurer will not deny claims or forfeit benefits based on fraud if the Insured Person can prove that any misstatement was true to the best of their knowledge and there was no deliberate intention to suppress facts or that the insurer knew about the misstatement.

In summary, attempting to submit fraudulent claims is forbidden and will result in loss of all benefits, forfeiture of premiums, and liability for repayment of any money paid. Successful fraudulent claims submission is therefore not possible under this policy as per the conditions stated.
